 Kellogg's is taking the British government to court over new rules that would limit the display of its cereals in  stores because of their high sugar content. New rules mean food and drink high in fat, salt or sugar  cannot be featured  at checkouts and aisle-ends in stores. Kellogg's, whose brands include Coco Pops, said the formula measuring the nutritional value of cereals was wrong. The department of health &  social care   declined to comment on  the Kellogg's case but said obesity costs the government Â£6bn (R119.8bn) a year. Reuters